library(TSA)

Examples of stochastic processes.

1. White noise.

Simulate a white noise series with \(t_9\) distribution.

n=200
set.seed(10) 
sim.white.noise=ts(rt(n, df=9), freq=1, start=1)
plot(sim.white.noise,type='o',ylab='t_9 white noise')




2. Random walk.

# Exhibit 2.1
data(rwalk) # rwalk contains a simulated random walk
plot(rwalk,type='o',ylab='Random Walk')

R code for simulating several runs of random walk with, say 60, iid standard normal errors.

n=60
set.seed(12345) # intialize the random number so that the simulation can be reproducible.
sim.random.walk=ts(cumsum(rnorm(n)),freq=1,start=1)
plot(sim.random.walk,type='o',ylab='Repeated Random Walks', ylim = c(-20, 20))
for (i in 1:10){
  points(ts(cumsum(rnorm(n)),freq=1,start=1), type = 'l', col = 'lightblue')
}




3. Moving average.

Use the simulated white noise from above, construct a two-point moving average series:

n=200
sim.moving.average=(sim.white.noise[1:(n-1)] + sim.white.noise[2:n])/2
plot(sim.white.noise,type='l',ylab='white noise and moving average')
points((1:(n-1))+0.5, sim.moving.average,type = 'o', col = 'blue')

Lets try a five-point moving average on the same series:

sim.moving.average2=(sim.white.noise[1:(n-4)] +
                       sim.white.noise[2:(n-3)] +
                       sim.white.noise[3:(n-2)] +
                       sim.white.noise[4:(n-1)] +
                       sim.white.noise[5:n])/5
plot(sim.white.noise,type='l',ylab='white noise and moving average')
points((1:(n-1))+0.5, sim.moving.average,type = 'l', col = 'blue')
points(3:(n-2), sim.moving.average2,type = 'o', col = 'red')

Note. White noise and moving average series are always stationary.




4. Random cosine wave.

We simulate a cosine wave with frequency \(1/12\) and a random phase, \(\Phi \sim Unif[0, 1]\).

t=1:60 # n=96
f=1/12 # frequency
set.seed(10)
sim.cos=cos(2*pi*f*(t+runif(1))) # cosine wave with random phase
plot(t, sim.cos, type='o', ylab='Cosines')

As we see the curve looks like its perfectly deterministic for one simulation. Lets do this a few times to see the variability.

plot(t, sim.cos, type='l', ylab='Cosines')
for (i in 1:10){
  sim.cos=cos(2*pi*f*(t+runif(1))) # cosine wave with random phase
  points(t, sim.cos, type='l', col = 'lightblue')
}





Deterministic Trends in Time Series.

A time series with no trend nor seasonality.

set.seed(100)
t=c(1:201)
y = 14.95 + rnorm(201)
plot(t,y, type="b",pch=16)

A time series with an additive linear trend.

set.seed(100)
t=c(1:201)
y = 20 + .05*t + rnorm(201)
plot(t,y, type="b",pch=16)

Fit a linear model to parse out the trend component: \[Y_t = \beta_0 + \beta_1 t + X_t\] Notice that the parameter values used for simulation is quite nicely recovered by the lm fit below.

out1 = lm(y ~ t)
summary(out1)

Cyclical and Seasonal trends.

The average monthly temperatures (in degrees Fahrenheit) over a number of years recorded in Dubuque, Iowa, are shown in Exhibit 1.7. This time series displays a very regular pattern called seasonality. Seasonality for monthly values occurs when observations twelve months apart are related in some manner or another. All Januarys and Februarys are quite cold but they are similar in value and different from the temperatures of the warmer months of June, July, and August, for example. There is still variation among the January values and variation among the June values.

Fit a seasonal means model, with one constant parameter per month, 12 total.

# Exhibit 1.7
data(tempdub)
plot(tempdub,type = 'b',cex=0.5,main = 'temperature data')

Note: with all 12 \(\beta\)s as well as the intercept, the linear model is no longer identifable so we must do something to make it identifiable, either by a) dropping the intercept term, or b) drop one of the \(\beta\)s. This is what model2 and model3 below did respectively.

# Exhibit 3.3
# season(tempdub) creates a vector of the month index of the data as a factor 
month.=season(tempdub) # the period sign is included to make the printout from the commands two line below clearer; ditto below.
model2=lm(tempdub~month.-1) # -1 removes the intercept term 
summary(model2)

Residual analysis.

Temperature data revisited. Exhibits 8-9: If the stochastic component is white noise and the trend is adequately modeled, we would expect such a plot to suggest a rectangular scatter with no discernible trends whatsoever. There are no striking departures from randomness apparent in this display.

# Exhibit 3.8
plot(y=rstudent(model3),x=as.vector(time(tempdub)),xlab='Time',ylab='Standardized Residuals',type='o')

Gross nonnormality can be assessed by plotting a histogram of the residuals or standardized residuals.

# Exhibit 3.11
hist(rstudent(model3),xlab='Standardized Residuals',main='')

and with QQ plot: displays the quantiles of the data versus the theoretical quantiles of a normal distribution. With normally distributed data, the QQ plot looks approximately like a straight line.

# Exhibit 3.12
qqnorm(rstudent(model3),main=''); qqline(rstudent(model3))



Shapiro-Wilk test.

S-W is a test of normality. It calculates the correlation between the residuals and the corresponding normal quantiles. The lower this correlation, the more evidence we have against normality.

shapiro.test(rstudent(model3))
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  rstudent(model3)
## W = 0.9929, p-value = 0.6954

Note the interpretation of the S-W test. A large p-value (e.g.>0.05) means we cannot reject the null hypothesis that the stochastic component of this model is normally distributed. On the other hand a small p-value rejects the null and provides evidence against the normality assumption.



The runs test.

Runs test is a test of independence. In the residual sequence, runs above or below their median are counted. Too many or two few runs will indeicate neighboring residuals are negatively and positive correlated, respectively, so either too few or too many runs lead us to reject independence.

runs(rstudent(model3))
## $pvalue
## [1] 0.216
## 
## $observed.runs
## [1] 65
## 
## $expected.runs
## [1] 72.875
## 
## $n1
## [1] 69
## 
## $n2
## [1] 75
## 
## $k
## [1] 0

A large p-value means we cannot reject the assumption of residual independence.



Sample Autocorrelation Function (ACF).

The sample ACF of lag \(k\) is given by \[\hat{\rho}_k = r_k = \frac{ \sum_{t=k+1}^n(y_t - \bar{y})(y_{t-k} - \bar{y})}{\sum_{t=1}^n (y_t - \bar{y})^2}\] where \(\bar{y} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{t=1}^n y_t\).

Example 1: seasonal means model of the temperature

Exhibit 3.13 displays the sample autocorrelation for the standardized residuals from the seasonal means model of the temperature series.For k = 1, 2,, 21, none of the hypotheses \(\rho_k = 0\) can be rejected at the usual significance levels, and it is reasonable to infer that the stochastic component of the series is white noise.

# Exhibit 3.13
acf(rstudent(model3),main='')

A third time series with a trend [revisited].

This is a time series simulated with a quadratic trend and a stochastic component (that is an Autoregressive(0.9) process).

set.seed(100)
t=c(1:201)
x = arima.sim(n = 201, list(ar=c(0.9)))
y = 14.95 - 0.08*t + 0.0006*(t^2)+x
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(t,y, type="b",pch=16)

To fit a quadratic trend to the model, create tsq which is the basis that is quadratic in time. The linear model is \[Y_t = \beta_0 + \beta_1 t + \beta_2 t^2 + X_t\]

tsq = t^2
out1 = lm(y ~  t + tsq)
summary(out1)
